                • Every woman covered under the Act is entitled to, and her employer is liable for, the payment of maternity leave at the rate of the average daily wage for the period of her actual absence immediately preceding and including the day of her delivery and for the six weeks immediately following that day. 
                • No woman is entitled to maternity leave unless she has actually worked in an establishment of the employer from whom she claims maternity leave for a period of not less than 80 days in the 12 months immediately preceding the date of her expected delivery. 
                • The maximum period for which any woman is entitled to maternity leave is 12 weeks, i.e. six weeks up to and including the day of her delivery and six weeks immediately following that day. 
                • No deduction from the normal and usual daily wages of a woman entitled to maternity leave shall be made by reason only of: (i) the nature of work assigned to her by virtue of the provisions of the Act; or (ii) breaks for nursing the child allowed to her under the provisions of the Act."

msgid "For breach of the provisions of the Act, the employer is punishable with imprisonment up to one year and/or a penalty of 5,000."
msgstr "For breach of the provisions of the Act, the employer is punishable with imprisonment up to one year and/or a penalty of 5,000."

msgid "The Act is applicable to employers employing categories of employees listed in Schedule II of the Act. It is applicable to all such employees irrespective of their status or salaries and engaged either directly or through a contractor or a person recruited to work abroad. Any employee who is injured by an accident arising out of and in the course of his employment, or contracts any occupational disease peculiar to his occupation, is eligible for various services under the Act. In case of death resulting from injury, 50% of monthly wages multiplied by (X) relevant factor or 1,20,000 Rs, whichever is more; in case of permanent total disablement resulting from the injury, 60% of monthly wages multiplied by relevant factor or 1,40,000 Rs, whichever is more; where permanent, partial disablement or temporary disablement results from injury, as per prescribed schedule, and in case of death, funeral expenses of 5,000Rs. The relevant factor is based on the age of the employee."
msgstr "The Act is applicable to employers employing categories of employees listed in Schedule II of the Act. It is applicable to all such employees irrespective of their status or salaries and engaged either directly or through a contractor or a person recruited to work abroad. Any employee who is injured by an accident arising out of and in the course of his employment, or contracts any occupational disease peculiar to his occupation, is eligible for various services under the Act. In case of death resulting from injury, 50% of monthly wages multiplied by (X) relevant factor or 1,20,000 Rs, whichever is more; in case of permanent total disablement resulting from the injury, 60% of monthly wages multiplied by relevant factor or 1,40,000 Rs, whichever is more; where permanent, partial disablement or temporary disablement results from injury, as per prescribed schedule, and in case of death, funeral expenses of 5,000Rs. The relevant factor is based on the age of the employee."

msgid "There is a provision for penalty under the Act for failure on the part of the employer to (a) to maintain a Notice-book which he is required to maintain under Sub-section (3) of Section 10, (b) failure to send to the Commissioner a statement which he is required to send under Sub-section (1) of Section 10A, (c) failure to send a report which he is required to send under Section 10B, and (d) failure to make a return which he is required to make under Section 16 of the Act. The above failures on the part of the employer are punishable with a penalty of 5,000Rs."
msgstr "There is a provision for penalty under the Act for failure on the part of the employer to (a) to maintain a Notice-book which he is required to maintain under Sub-section (3) of Section 10, (b) failure to send to the Commissioner a statement which he is required to send under Sub-section (1) of Section 10A, (c) failure to send a report which he is required to send under Section 10B, and (d) failure to make a return which he is required to make under Section 16 of the Act. The above failures on the part of the employer are punishable with a penalty of 5,000Rs."

msgid "In a nutshell, the Act's provisions provide that no child shall be obliged or allowed to work in any establishment for more hours than may be allowed for that establishment or type of establishments. Each day's work period must be adjusted such that it never exceeds three hours. It also states that no youngster should work for longer than three hours without a break for rest. No youngster shall be required to work overtime or be permitted to do so."
msgstr "In a nutshell, the Act's provisions provide that no child shall be obliged or allowed to work in any establishment for more hours than may be allowed for that establishment or type of establishments. Each day's work period must be adjusted such that it never exceeds three hours. It also states that no youngster should work for longer than three hours without a break for rest. No youngster shall be required to work overtime or be permitted to do so."

msgid "Section 3 of the Act states the prohibited occupations and processes, whoever employs any child or permits any child to work in contravention of the provisions of Sec. 3 shall be punishable with imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than, three months but which may extend to one year or with fine which shall not be less than ten thousand rupees but which may extend to twenty thousand rupees or with both. Repeat offence under section 3 is punishable with imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than six months but which may extend to two years."
msgstr "Section 3 of the Act states the prohibited occupations and processes, whoever employs any child or permits any child to work in contravention of the provisions of Sec. 3 shall be punishable with imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than, three months but which may extend to one year or with fine which shall not be less than ten thousand rupees but which may extend to twenty thousand rupees or with both. Repeat offence under section 3 is punishable with imprisonment for a term which shall not be less than six months but which may extend to two years."


